</v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img width=3D187 height=3D183
src=3D"UI_ShipMissions_files/image004.png" align=3Dright hspace=3D12 v:shap=
es=3D"Picture_x0020_1"><![endif]><span
style=3D'mso-no-proof:yes'>If more than one mission is available then a pop=
-up
menu appears with detailed mission options. Select one of the options from =
the
menu to assign a mission. You can also force a pop-up menu to appear with a=
ll
available missions for the selected ship by holding down the Ctrl key and
right-clicking.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'mso-no-proof:yes'>Some missions are also
available as Action buttons under the Selection Panel. Click an Action butt=
on
to assign the mission to the selected ship.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<h3><span style=3D'mso-no-proof:yes'>Automating your ships<o:p></o:p></span=
></h3>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'mso-no-proof:yes'>State-owned ships can=
 be
automated so that they assign their own missions appropriate to their type.
(Privately-owned ships are always automated &#8211; you cannot assign missi=
ons
to them)<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'mso-no-proof:yes'>To automate a ship, s=
elect it
and then press the &#8216;A&#8217; key. To stop automation just assign a
mission to the ship. You can also toggle automation on or off using the Act=
ion
button under the Selection Panel.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'mso-no-proof:yes'>Note that after being=
 built,
all ships start off fully automated.</span></p>

</div>

